----------Topic Jan----------

Idee: Studi Wohngegenden Analysieren in Kiel

The poject analyzes the relationship between different types of transport, maynly Car, Bus and Bike in kiel, regarding different weather metrics like temperature, rain, snow and so on. The project will use data from official car traffic data, official KVG data, bike data from Nextbike and bike counting stations, as well as weather data from open Meteo Wetter API.

Data sources:
-Car data from 27 official car counting stations in Kiel 

-Bike data from official bike counting stations in Kiel
	https://mobilithek.info/offers/784002906756923392
-Bike data from Nextbike, a bike sharing company in Kiel
	https://api.nextbike.net/api/doc.php?mode=classic-regular&apikey=

-Bus data from KVG, the public transport company in Kiel
	https://opendata.schleswig-holstein.de/dataset/passagiere-landverkehr-der-kieler-verkehrsgesellschaft

-Weather data from open Meteo Wetter API
	https://open-meteo.com/

----------Topic Nico----------
The project analyzes how Trump-related news reporting (categorized by topic: trade policy, geopolitics, domestic politics) correlates with short-term price changes in three asset classes of varying volatility – MSCI World (low), Gold (medium), and Bitcoin (high) – during Trump's current legislative period starting January 2025. News data is sourced from The Guardian API, market data via yfinance. Articles are evaluated using keyword-frequency-based categorization; results are visualized in a web application.

Research question 1: (Nico)
To what extent does the frequency of Trump-related news coverage, categorized by topic (trade policy, geopolitics, domestic politics), correlate with short-term price changes (1–3 trading days) in MSCI World, Gold, and Bitcoin?

Resarch question 2: (Nico)
Do different asset classes (MSCI World, Gold, Bitcoin) show distinct or similar price reactions to the same categories of Trump-related news events, and what does this reveal about their role as safe-haven or risk assets?

Research question 3: (Nico)
Which news category (trade policy, geopolitics, or domestic politics) shows the strongest association with market movements across all three asset classes?

Research question 4: (Jan)
What is the average time that the markets need to react to different news types? What news types show their effects the fastest?

Research question 5: (Jan)
Is there a news threashold, like a minimum number of news articles on one topic befor the markets show a response on news? If yes what is that threshhold?

Research question 6: (Fridjoff)
Does the sentiment (positive, negative, neutral) of Trump-related news within each category (trade policy, geopolitics, domestic politics) influence the direction and magnitude of short-term price reactions in MSCI World, Gold, and Bitcoin?

Research question 7: (Fridjoff)
Are market reactions to Trump-related news asymmetric, meaning do negative news events trigger stronger short-term price movements than positive news events across MSCI World, Gold, and Bitcoin?

